[2] South Korea, 2 new contact cases - media report, RFI
Date: Thu 21 May 2015
Source: Yahoo News, Reuters report [edited]
http://news.yahoo.com/south-korea-confirms-second-case-mers-virus-third-022536212.html


South Korean health officials confirmed the country's 3rd case of Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) on Thursday [21 May 2015], with the 2 latest cases found in people who had been in contact with the 1st patient after he returned from the Middle East.

Authorities have isolated as a precaution another 64 people who are family members or medical workers treating those 3 patients, said Yang Byung-guk, director of the health ministry's Korea Centers for Disease Control & Prevention.

Test results came back positive for a 63 year old woman, the wife of the 1st proven case, as well as for a 76 year old man who shared a hospital room with him, the ministry said.

The 1st man was diagnosed with the disease on Wednesday [20 May 2015] after a trip to Bahrain, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates [the original report posted yesterday stated the individual was in Bahrain and transferred flights in Qatar - Mod.MPP], where the disease broke out, Yang told a briefing.

Shin Hyoung-shik, an infectious disease specialist in charge of treating the patients, said the latest 2 confirmed cases had fevers but no sign of breathing difficulties. "The 1st patient has been recovering, with less difficulty in breathing," Shin said.

The ministry said on Wednesday [20 May 2015] it saw no chance of the disease spreading into the wider population because those who had been in contact with the 1st patient had been isolated.

The disease's fatality rate is 30-40 per cent and its incubation period is 2 to 14 days, experts say. "The 40 per cent death rate is quite high," Choi Jun-yong, an associate professor at the infectious diseases division of Severance Hospital, told Reuters by telephone. "If infected, patients in many cases need to have artificial respiration treatments for respiratory failures."

First identified in humans in 2012, MERS is caused by a coronavirus, from the same family as the one that caused a deadly outbreak of severe acute respiratory syndrome [SARS] in China in 2003. There is no cure or vaccine.

South Korea's health ministry said 23 countries had a combined 1142 cases of MERS and 465 deaths had been reported, as of [16 May 2015]. Of the total, 1117 cases, or 97.8 per cent, were in the Middle East. [These numbers come from the ECDC Communicable Disease Threat's report of 16 May 2015, available at http://ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/Publications/communicable-disease-threats-report-16-may-2015.pdf. - Mod.MPP]

There is usually a surge of cases in the northern spring and most cases have come from hospital transmission."

[byline: Meeyoung Cho]

