******
[3] South Korea, new contact cases, media report
Date: Thu 21 May 2015
Source: Korea Joongang Daily [edited]
http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3004499


South Korea on Thursday [21 May 2015] confirmed a 3rd case of Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS), which was found in an elderly man who shared a hospital room with the country's 1st patient.

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) announced on Wednesday [20 May 2015] that a 68 year old man who had traveled to Bahrain for about 3 weeks and returned to Korea earlier this month [May 2015] was found to have been infected with MERS and subsequently transmitted it to his 63 year old wife. In a subsequent report on Thursday [21 May 2015], CDC added that a 76 year old patient who spent 5 hours in the same room with the 1st MERS patient had contracted the disease while being treated on Saturday [16 May 2015] at a general hospital in Seoul. However, none of the 3 victims is in a critical condition, according to the authority.

MERS was 1st reported in Saudi Arabia in 2012 and is most prevalent in the Middle East. The disease has a latent period of up to 2 weeks and presents flu-like symptoms. According to the European Center for Disease Prevention and Control, a total of 1142 people had been diagnosed with the disease as of [16 May 2015], and so far it has resulted in 465 deaths, showing a 40.7 per cent fatality rate. No vaccines or cures have been developed yet.

The new infections have since raised questions over the quarantine authority's detection system. The 1st patient reportedly traveled to Bahrain on [18 Apr 2015], and on to Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and Qatar, before coming back to Korea on [4 May 2015] via Incheon International Airport. The man passed through a heat sensor, though at the time, the quarantine authority did not detect anything out of the ordinary.

Despite the fact that the patient had visited Saudi Arabia, where 428 people have died of MERS, airport officials at the National Quarantine Station (NQS) have been criticized for lax safety procedures, only measuring the 68-year-old's body temperature. Officials at the NQS, a subdivision of CDC, are supposed to ask incoming passengers about any obvious symptoms -- especially if travelers have visited any countries with a high risk for contagious diseases -- and report any abnormalities later on. "We are going to make every single passenger on flights from the Middle East [4 times a day] write declaration forms and conduct individual interviews when they pass through Immigration," said an official at the NQS at the Incheon International Airport.

The 1st patient reportedly began to show symptoms on [11 May 2015], a week after his return, and when the man visited a local clinic, he was prescribed cold medicine. After his symptoms worsened, he was admitted to a general hospital, where the 3rd patient was infected as the 2 men shared a hospital room.

"The spray from a sneeze or a cough can travel up to 2 meters [6.6 feet], and it's possible that a person staying in the same room can be infected," said Kim Woo-joo, a professor at Korea University. "There have also been secondary infection cases reported between patients and medical staff in foreign countries like Saudi Arabia."

As the 1st patient's condition gradually deteriorated, he was transferred on Sunday [17 May 2015] to a larger general hospital in Seoul. But because the hospital was full, he stayed the night in an adjacent clinic and was finally admitted to the general hospital on Monday [18 May 2015].

A doctor at the hospital reported the case to CDC, though the man was only isolated since Wednesday [20 May 2015] after the results of a blood test came back positive. CDC is currently monitoring 64 people, including medical staff and the family members who came in contact with the 3 patients.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This now makes 2 locally transmitted contact cases reported from South Korea associated with the 1st imported case. In the original media report there was mention of travel to Bahrain for farm related work and return to Korea via Qatar. This current report adds travel to Saudi Arabia and the UAE, both locations with recent evidence of MERS-CoV circulation (see MERS-CoV (44): S Korea ex Middle East, Saudi Arabia, UAE, WHO, RFI 20150520.3374579 for more details.). Clarification of potential risk exposures while in the Middle East and locations of exposures of the 1st case would be greatly appreciated. As for the nosocomial transmission, perhaps the time has come for universal respiratory precautions when a patient is admitted to a hospital for a febrile respiratory illness ... clearly we see nosocomial enhancement of transmission of disease.

The media report above suggests that the infections were confirmed through serologic testing as there is no mention of PCR results. Will this testing be accepted as confirmation of infection?

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of the region showing Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates (UAE) can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3378310,131, and the HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of South Korea can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3378310,195. - Mod.MPP]
